#  Day 67 – Task R-4: The Authorization Decision | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Moment Everything Has Been Building Toward

Day 66 produced the formal risk response documentation — ten open POA&M items with their response types, responsible parties, and timelines, plus a brief organizational risk appetite statement establishing that patient safety implications are treated as Moderate or higher regardless of technical severity rating. The AO reviewed the risk response record and confirmed the decisions documented there.

Task R-4 is the authorization decision itself: the AO's formal, signed determination that the system is authorized to operate — or that it is not. Every document produced since Day 1 of this project has been preparation for this moment. The SSP described the system and its controls. The SAR evaluated whether those controls were implemented and effective. The POA&M committed to remediating the gaps. The risk response record documented how each residual risk will be handled. Task R-4 is where the AO synthesizes all of that into a single, binding decision.

I want to be honest about what an ATO actually is before describing MyClinic's — because the casual framing ("the system is cleared to go live") understates both what the ATO represents and what it does not represent.

An ATO is a formal acceptance of residual risk by a designated official who has the organizational authority to make that acceptance on behalf of the organization. It is not a certification that the system is secure. It is not a guarantee that no breach will occur. It is a documented, reasoned judgment that the system's security posture — with its implemented controls, its open remediation items, its compensating controls, and its continuous monitoring program — represents an acceptable risk level for the organization to operate the system in pursuit of its mission.

That distinction matters because it defines what happens after the ATO is issued. The ATO is not the end of security work — it is the formal beginning of the operating-with-accountability phase.

