## What the ATO Means Operationally

The signed Authorization Decision Document transitions MyClinic's OpenMRS from a system under development and assessment to a system under formal authorization and continuous monitoring. Concretely, this means:

The ISSO's work shifts from project-mode (producing documents toward an authorization) to operations-mode (maintaining the security posture documented in those papers, executing the continuous monitoring strategy, and managing the POA&M).

The 90-day CP-2 condition is now a binding organizational commitment with the Executive Director's name on it — not a security team to-do item. The Health IT Manager is accountable to the AO, and the AO has a calendar entry for the 45-day check-in.

The quarterly POA&M report is now a formal governance deliverable, not a discretionary update. The ISSO's calendar reminder for quarterly POA&M review — established after the AT-2 quarterly review lapse — is the operational mechanism that makes this work.

The continuous monitoring strategy produces the evidence that the authorization remains valid. If monitoring reveals that controls are no longer effective — a new critical vulnerability, a configuration drift, a monitoring gap — that evidence feeds back into the AO's awareness through the Material Risk Change Notification condition.

