## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

Drafting the authorization conditions with explicit verification standards — not just "complete CP-2" but "Health IT Manager and clinical leadership approval signatures on completed document plus ISSO documentation of tabletop walkthrough" — was directly informed by how I think about the **2015 Premera Blue Cross breach** and its OCR enforcement outcome.

The OCR investigation that followed the Premera breach found that Premera had conducted risk analyses — the HIPAA equivalent of the RMF assessment process — but that those analyses were not followed by adequate risk management activity. Specifically, OCR found that Premera had identified vulnerabilities in prior risk analyses, had risk management plans in place, but that the plans were not executed in a way that actually reduced the identified risks within defined timelines.

The $6.85 million settlement included a corrective action plan requiring Premera to implement a comprehensive risk management program with specific, verifiable milestones.

The lesson I took from the Premera case for today's authorization conditions is that conditions without verification standards are conditions that can be satisfied on paper without being satisfied in substance. "Complete clinical downtime procedures within 90 days" could be satisfied by a two-paragraph draft. "Complete clinical downtime procedures covering all six functional areas, approved by clinical leadership, and tested in a tabletop walkthrough, verified by specific signatures and documentation" cannot be satisfied without the actual work being done.

Verification standards turn authorization conditions from aspirational commitments into accountable deliverables. The Premera case shows what happens when the governance structure lacks that specificity — plans exist, but execution does not follow, and the gap between documented intent and operational reality is where breaches happen.

