## What I Am Still Thinking About

The four-year cumulative arc of this project — from Day 1's introduction to GRC concepts through today's signed ATO — raises a question I want to sit with as we enter the Monitor step: what does it mean for security program sustainability that so much of what was built here depended on one person's initiative?

The ISSO drove the SSP, the control implementations, the POA&M, the assessment preparation, the remediation actions, and the authorization package. The Health IT Manager and Compliance Officer were engaged and cooperative, but the security program's existence and quality are largely attributable to one dedicated individual.

This is realistic for a small clinic — MyClinic cannot afford a security team. But it also means the security program has a single point of failure that no technical control can address. If the ISSO leaves, the institutional knowledge of why controls were implemented the way they were, which POA&M items are genuinely high-risk versus administrative, and how the continuous monitoring program is designed to function — all of that walks out the door.

The Monitor step documentation, the SSP version history, the POA&M with its rationale notes — these are the organization's investment against that human continuity risk. The better the documentation, the less any single person's departure disrupts the security program. This is one more reason why documentation quality is not a compliance box to check but a genuine organizational resilience investment.

